    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, yes, your professor was referring to Albert Einstein's famous description of quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance.\" He found it strange because it seemed to challenge his belief in local realism, the idea that objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings. In the world of quantum physics, this \"spookiness\" arises because entangled particles appear to communicate instantaneously, defying our everyday understanding of how the universe works. It's like having a pair of magical dice that always land on the same number, even if one is far away, which seems to violate the speed limit set by the speed of light. This \"spooky\" behavior is not yet fully understood, but it's one of the most fascinating and mysterious aspects of quantum mechanics. It's like a secret language that only the entangled particles understand, and scientists are still trying to decode it.",
